							<!-- End each blog post -->
							
														
							<div class="post_wrapper author">
								<div id="about_the_author">
									<div class="gravatar"><a href="https://lithub.com/author/adamehrlichsachs/"><img src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/adam-ehrlich-sachs-100x100.jpeg" width="100" height="100" alt="Adam Ehrlich Sachs" class="avatar avatar-100 wp-user-avatar wp-user-avatar-100 alignnone photo" /></a></div>
									<div class="description author withsidebar">
										<h6><a href="https://lithub.com/author/adamehrlichsachs/">Adam Ehrlich Sachs</a></h6>
										Adam Ehrlich Sachs is the author of the collection Inherited Disorders: Stories, Parables, and Problems, which was a semifinalist for the Thurber Prize for American Humor and a finalist for the Sami Rohr Prize for Jewish Literature. His work has appeared in <em>The New Yorker, Harper’s Magazine</em>, and <em>n+1</em>, among other publications, and he was named a 2018 National Endowment for the Arts Literature Fellow. He has a degree in the history of science from Harvard, where he was a member of The Harvard Lampoon, and currently lives in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania. <em>The Organs of Sense</em> (FSG) is his first novel.																			</div>
								</div><br class="clear"/><br/>
							</div>
